			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I was thinking about something related to this earlier, might as well mention it here.  
<br />

<br />
Does it seem like it would be unbalancing to have a quest that would provide Magicians with Rentable, No Drop versions of the summoned focus items?  The Ornate Orb of Mastery solution is what made me think of this.  Basically you would hand an NPC one of the summoned items and perhaps some other item(s) to make it require some work to obtain, and he would hand you back a "special" version of the same item.  Like:
<br />

<br />
Gallenite's Tangible Sapphire Bracelet
<br />
MAGIC ITEM LORE ITEM NO DROP
<br />
Slot: WRIST
<br />
AC: 8
<br />
HP: +20 MANA: +20
<br />
Required level of 61.
<br />
Focus: Gallenite's Chaos
<br />
WT: 0.1 Size: TINY
<br />
Class: MAG
<br />
Race: HUM ERU HIE DEF GNM
<br />

<br />
The class restriction and required level would prevent anybody incapable of actually casting the spell from getting their hands on one, though I suppose it'd still allow Magicians who were of the appropriate level but didn't actually have the spell to get one.  I don't really see this as being an issue though, as I just dinged 61 tonight and was able to easily acquire all of the focus items in the bazaar with very little plat expended.
<br />

<br />
Anyway, this would be pretty much for convenience and nothing more.  It would mainly save those of us who don't have focus items better than what we can summon from having to conjure up a set upon logging in, and would save us from having to give away the focus items we're wearing when somebody requests one (I hope I'm not the only one who occasionally summons up a bracelet or ring when asked for one, forgetting about the item that I'm currently wearing).  It would also fix the jewelry bag issue.
<br />

<br />
/shrug
<br />

<br />
I fully admit that these are all minor inconveniences.  I'm certainly not complaining about the fact that I have to summon my focus items whenever I log in, especially with the advent of the /mem command.  This is just an idea I had for a fairly simple fix to some fairly trivial annoyances...</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
