			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Hmmmm, just thinking about this issue from the point of view of the EQ development team.
<br />

<br />
* Current system is not broken, conjured items can be cast
<br />
* System is working as intended
<br />
* Players have item conjuration restrictions so that they must either:
<br />
     - conjure lore items and distribute before having for themselves
<br />
     - conjure items for people in advance, and drop on the ground. Items must be claimed within the decay time.
<br />
* Any time a change is made to items in the game, it opens up some unexpected possibility of exploitation. An example would be targetted summons, in which such a thing interferes with the PvP environment, or is used to harass another player.
<br />

<br />

<br />
So, what we are asking for is a modification that removes a frustration that we see, but it doesn't really come out as a major issue.  They probably have plenty of things to address programming wise. The more coding changes we ask for and the further the change from what we have, the less likely we will get it or the more likely it will be dropped on the "to-do" priority list.
<br />

<br />
Changing the lore status on the items might mean the least amount of programming for the biggest fix ot the issue.  The targetable summons would be great, but I would think they might need to add a character flag that lets you receive summons or not, so the targetted player has the choice to receive it or not.
<br />

<br />
The Lore change is in my mind the biggest bang-for-the-programming-buck, but is it still big enough to warrant assigning programming time and testing time, and time to test the migration to live databases? Possibly its just a database change, but it might not be.
<br />

<br />
I think we still need to have a more powerful reason for requesting even the minimal change from lore to non-lore, let alone more significant changes.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
