			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Targetted summons would make life so much easier.  Maybe restrict it to group or raid members only if setting an option to disable targetted summons isn't feasible.  
<br />

<br />
With all the changes to make EQ life easier and more convenient, it seems unfair that mages are stuck jumping through hoops for our utility spells, especially focus items.  
<br />

<br />
If you are wearing even one summoned focus item and a raid member requests a jewelry bag you need to destroy the item(s) you're wearing.  Then cast the spell and either drop the bag (which seems kind of rude, especially if the raid is moving) or hunt down this person and attempt to open a trade window.  A lot of the time they will be busy casting when you get to them, or won't click O.K. for several seconds.  Now you need to cast the spell again, dig through the bag, and re-equip yourself.  Takes you about a full minute or more just to do the equivalent of "buffing" your raid member.  
<br />

<br />
Other classes don't understand the inconvenience and probably don't think any more of asking for focus items than sending a tell for Brells Stalwart Shield, which is part of the problem.  If they had any idea, they would ask for them during buffing or not at all.
<br />

<br />
Simply removing the lore tag only removes half the problem, and has the issue of bazaar mules stocked full of focus gear.  (I wouldn't mind this actually, since if people can buy them easily maybe they wouldn't come looking for me).
<br />

<br />
In reality, this doesn't just effect mages, but also everyone that plays with mages.  If a warrior sends a tell for arrows and I drop 10 stacks and he has to come and try to pick them up, it is a much bigger pain in the butt than if the items landed on his cursor and he could just drop them in the auto equip box.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
